\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:introduction"

\end_inset

[Placeholder introduction.
 This section lays out the narrative arc of the paper.
 Markets for quality require that quality be observable to both buyers and
 sellers.
 In many agricultural value chains in developing countries, quality is difficult
 to measure, leading to classic lemons problems where high-quality producers
 are not rewarded and have little incentive to invest in quality.
 We study whether introducing measurement technology---milk analyzers that
 can objectively assess fat content and solids-not-fat---can catalyze the
 emergence of quality-differentiated pricing in Ugandan dairy supply chains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experiment 1 introduces milk analyzers to randomly selected Milk Collection
 Centers (MCCs) and an information video to randomly selected farmers in
 a 2x2 factorial design.
 We find that quality measurement technology improves milk quality practices
 and reduces adulteration, but does not lead to quality-differentiated pricing.
 This is an enforcement equilibrium, not a market for quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To rationalize these findings, we develop a simple model in which a parameter
 alpha governs the extent to which measurement technology is used for price
 differentiation versus enforcement.
 When alpha equals zero, the technology is used purely for enforcement; when
 alpha is positive, prices are differentiated by quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experiment 2 directly tests the price channel by introducing quality bonuses
 at MCCs that already have analyzers.
 We find that activating the price channel through explicit bonuses elicits
 further quality improvements, confirming that the missing ingredient was
 not information but price incentives.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Context: Dairy Supply Chains in Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:context"

\end_inset

[Placeholder section on the Ugandan dairy sector context.
 Describe the structure of dairy supply chains: smallholder farmers sell
 milk to Milk Collection Centers (MCCs), which aggregate and cool milk before
 selling to processors.
 Some farmers sell directly to MCCs while others sell through traders/middlemen.
 Quality is difficult to observe without testing equipment.
 Adulteration (primarily water addition) is a widespread problem.
 MCCs vary in organizational form (cooperatives vs.
 private) and capacity.]
\end_layout

