\begin_layout Section
A Model of Measurement Technology and Quality Incentives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:model"

\end_inset

This section presents a simple model to rationalize the findings from Experiment
 1.
 The model shows how measurement technology can improve quality through
 two distinct channels---enforcement and price differentiation---and how
 the relative importance of these channels depends on a single parameter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Placeholder for model setup.
 Consider an MCC that procures milk from farmers.
 The MCC has access to a measurement technology that reveals milk quality
 (fat content, adulteration).
 The parameter alpha in [0,1] governs how the MCC uses this information:]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[When alpha = 0, the MCC uses the technology purely for enforcement: milk
 below a minimum quality threshold is rejected, but all accepted milk receives
 the same price.
 This is an enforcement-only equilibrium.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[When alpha > 0, the MCC uses the technology for price differentiation:
 higher-quality milk receives a higher price.
 The strength of the price channel is increasing in alpha.]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[Placeholder for model predictions.
 The model nests two channels:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Enforcement channel (alpha = 0): Technology reduces adulteration by raising
 the probability of detection and rejection.
 Quality improves but prices do not differentiate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Price channel (alpha > 0): Technology enables quality-differentiated pricing,
 providing continuous incentives for quality improvement beyond the minimum
 threshold.]
\end_layout

